Track Popularity Prediction Report

Data Science 2 with R (STAT 301-2)

Author

Stephanie Xu

Introduction

What is the secret or tactic of making a hit song? Can we predict the publicâs response to a song before it is released? For young musicians who want to gain more exposure and reputation, producing a hit song may be the best way to accomplish this goal.

Therefore, I will build a model to predict the popularity of a track. The dataset I will use is the Spotify Tracks Dataset published on kaggle and contributed by Maharshi Pandya. The dataset contains Spotify tracks over a range of 125 different genres and some audio features associated with each track. The response variable I choose is popularity which is in the most part calculated by algorithm and is based on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are.

The model can be used by either song creators or music labels who want to improve their performance in making a well-known song and can adjust the audio features of their music according to the parameters of the model before releasing songs.

The raw dataset have 114000 observations and 21 variables in total, including 5 characters, 4 factors, and 12 numerical variables. Among them, artists, album_name, and track_name each has one missingness. Using the function I defined get_NA(), I found out that all the missingness occurs in one row. Since I will not consider artists, album_name, and track_name as my predictors, I chose to keep this row.

Exploration of the Response Variable

The graph below reveals the distribution of the response variable popularity. It is a numerical variable and is left-skewed. One thing to be noticed is that among 114000 observations, more than 17500 have a popularity value of 0 which accounts for more than 1/10 of the total observations. This means that near 1/10 of the songs in the dataset are not popular at all.

Despite the zeros, the distribution of poopularity is slightly left skewed, so I wonât apply transformation to it. When splitting the dataset, strata = popularity is needed to deal with the issues with zeros.

Exploration of other categorical variables

explicit

The non-explicit category has considerably more observations than the explicit category. The number of non-explicit tracks is approximately 9 times the number of explicit tracks.

track_genre

The raw dataset takes 1000 samples for each genre, so categories of genre are well balanced.

mode

The variable mode also has the imbalance issue. The number of tracks in the dataset written in major (represented by 1) are approximately twice the tracks written in minor (represented by 2)

key

Variation exists in the number of tracks in each key. Dâ¯/Eâ­ (represented by 3) has the least number of tracks while C (0) and Fâ¯/Gâ­ (7) have the most number of tracks.

time_signature

More than 70% of the tracks have a time_signature of 4, which represents the 4/4 time signature. Other tracks scatter in the 0, 1, 2, 3, and 5 category.

Data spending

The ratio I chose to split the dataset is 0.65: 65% of the observation go to the training set and 35% of the observation goes to the testing dataset. The reasoning behind this is to save time while using the training dataset to tune parameters for models.

Further EDA and feature engineering

Correlation between numerical variables and popularity

The correlation between other numerical variables and popularity is shown in the graph below.

The six numerical variables that have the highest correlation with popularity are instrumentalness, loudness, speechiness, valence, danceability and acousticness (correlation from high to low). They are considered potential predictors for the model.

Relationship between categorical variables and popularity

Relationship between explicit and popularity

The graph below shows the distribution of popularity in each explicit category.

The median of popularity belongs to the TRUE category is higher than the FALSE category. In addition, when looking at the first and third quartile, those of the TRUE category are also greater than those of the FALSE category. Thus explicit tracks in general are more popular than non-explicit tracks. However, it is possible that higher overall popularity in the TRUE category is a result of severe class imbalance. To exclude this interference, I will not consider explicit as a predictor.

Relationship between track_genre and popularity

The following graph reveals the distribution of popularity of each genre. It is very clear some genres are very welcomed by the public while some are not. For example, pop, pop_film, k-pop, hip-pop and metal are the most popular genre.

However, as it will be extremely time consuming to tune parameters and fit models if include track_genre with 125 categories as a predictor, I will not choose track_genre as a predictor.

Relationship between mode and popularity

Distribution of popularity of tracks in major (1) is very similar to minor (2), so mode is not considered as a predictor.

Relationship between time_signature and popularity

Variations in the medians of popularity of different time_signature exist when looking at the boxplot below. It is possible that time_signature can be used to predict popularity.

Relationship between time_signature and popularity

The medians of popularity donât have significant variation for each key value, and thus key is not considered a predictor.

Methods

Recipes

  • Recipe 1 is the standard/basic recipe for models. Predictors include six numerical predictors which have highest correlation with popularity in the correlation test- instrumentalness,loudness, speechiness, valence, danceabilityand accousticness- and one categorical predictor time_signature.
  • Recipe 2 is the variation of Recipe 1. I remove instrumentalness from predictors to explore the importance of instrumentalness in predicting popularity.
  • Recipe 3 is also the variation of Recipe 1. I remove loudness from predictors to explore the importance of loudness in predicting popularity

Resampling Technique

I use cross-validation with 5 folds and 3 repeats as a resampling technique. During this process, the training dataset will be split into 5 folds. The model will be trained on 4 folds and tested on the other fold. The performance of the model on the testing fold will be recorded. Then the iteration continues until each folds has been used for testing once. This whole process will repeat for 3 times, giving a total of 5*3 = 15 estimations.

Models and Model Setup

All the models I select were set to regression mode and for predictive purposes. The grid search method is applied for finding the optimal parameter. I chose a regular grid and 5 levels per parameter. However, for Random Forest and Boosted Tree, I set 3 levels per parameter to reduce the time spent on tuning.

Null Model

A null model is used to draw the baseline for the model performance. Any model have poorer performance than this baseline will be meaningless for prediction.

OLS linear regression

  • This model chooses unknown parameters by the principle of least squares, that is minimizing the sum of the squares of the differences between true response variable and the predicted response variable.
  • No parameter will be tuned.

Elastic Net Regularization

  • Elastic net is a regularized regression method that linearly combines the L1 and L2 penalties of the lasso and ridge methods.
  • mixture and penalty are two parameters need to be tuned. mixture determines the level of combination of lasso and ridge, and penalty determines the penalty value.

Random Forest

  • A decision tree method for prediction.
  • mtry, min_n, and trees are parameters need to be tuned. mtry is usually the number of sampled predictors. min_n is the number of data points to split. trees is the number of decision trees to create and usually need not to be tuned as long as itâs large enough. In this project the trees will be set to 2000.

Boosted Tree

  • Different from Random Forest, each tree in the Boosted Tree method is trained on the residuals from the previous sequence of trees.
  • mtry, min_n, learn_rate, and trees are parameters need to be tuned. While other parameters have the same function as the Random Forest, learn_rate denotes the weight for the influence of each new tree ranging between 0 and 1.

Kth Nearest Neighbor

  • In KNN regression, given a query point, the algorithm finds the K training points that are closest to the query point in terms of some distance metric. It then takes the average (or median) of the target values of those K points and uses it as the predicted target value for the query point.
  • neighbors is the parameter needs to be tuned.

Evaluation metrics

  • RMSE: it computes the root mean squared error between the actual response variable and the predicted response variable. The lower the RMSE value, the better the prediction.
  • \(R^2\): it measures how much variability in dependent variable can be explained by the model and ranges from 0 to 1. The closest the \(R^2\) to 1, the better the estimation.

Note that the \(R^2\) value of the null model is NaN, which probably indicates that there is no linear relationship between predictors and the response variable.

Choosing Optimal Recipe and importance of predictors.

I calculated the mean RMSE and \(R^2\) for each recipe. Recipe 1, the standard recipe is the winning recipe with lowest RMSE at 19.7481 and highest \(R^2\) at 0.2237.

Recipe 2 is obtained by removing intrumentalness from predictors. The RMSE is increased by 0.22 and \(R^2\) is decreased by 0.015 after doing this.

Recipe 3 is obtained by removing loudness from predictors. The RMSE is increased by 0.08 and \(R^2\) is decreased by 0.008 after doing this.

Both predictors have influences on the performance of the model, while instrumentalness is more important in predicting values for popularity compared to loundess.

Best parameters for each model type

Here I visualize the change in RMSE when parameters change for each model. Only models tuned with Recipe 1 are chosen because Recipe 1 is the optimal recipe.

Random Forest

A pattern can be observed is that the smaller the minimal node size, the better the prediction. However, if the minimal node size is too small, it is possible to lead to overfitting.

For mtry, when minimal node size is at 21 and 40, increase in mtry can result in more accurate prediction. But it is not the case when minimal node size is at 2. The increase in mtry can make the prediction less accurate. As there are only three levels for mtry and min_n, a conclusion of how the change in parameters can affect performance of the model cannot be made due to lack of information.

Boosted Tree

It is very clear that more trees (in thousands) will lead to better prediction. The influence of learn rate is also very obvious: higher learn rate can significantly reduce the RMSE. But from my results, the change in minimal node size doesnât have very strong impact on the RMSE.

KNN

From the graph above, the RMSE decreases as the number of nearest neighbors increase. The change is most drastic when the number of nearest neighbor increases from 1 to 4, and the pace of decreasing slows down when the number of nearest neighbor is greater than 4.

Elastic Net

When the penalty is at a very small scales, the change of penalty have subtle impact on RMSE. Once the penalty is greater than a certain level, the increase of penalty lead to increase in RMSE.

The minimum RMSE occurs when the mixture is 0.0500. As mixture increases, the RMSE also increases.

The winning model

After comparison above, I concluded that the random forest model with recipe 1 is the winning model, with parameters mtry = 5 and min_n = 2. This model has the lowest RMSE and highest \(R^2\) value, indicating that this model has the lowest estimation error and 44.68% of the variability observed in popularity is explained by the regression model.

The result is not surprising because the \(R^2\) for null model NaN, indicating that thereâs no linear relationship or very little linear relationship between predictors and popularity. The \(R^2\) value of OLS models and Elastic Net Models ranges between 0.013 and 0.023, also implies that the linear relationship is very weak. In this situation, tree models and KNN model usually outperform the linear models.

Final Model Analysis

At the final stage, I used the training dataset to fit the winning model- Random Forest with trees = 1000,mtry = 5 and min_n = 2 and Recipe 1 (predictors include instrumentalness,loudness, speechiness, valence, danceability, accousticness and time_signature). Next, the fitted model will be used to predict the popularity with the test dataset.

The performance of this final model is even better than the best performing random forest model at the validation stage.

# A tibble: 2 Ã 3
  .metric .estimator .estimate
  <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
1 rmse    standard      16.1  
2 rsq     standard       0.484

The RMSE is 0.5764 lower than the previous winning model, and the \(R^2\) is 0.0373 higher than the previous one.

The following graph visualizes how well the model predict the popularity.

If the prediction is exactly the true value of popularity, all the data points will align on the solid line.

The observed distribution of the data point can be categorized into three groups: one group of data points distributed approximately along the solid line, one group of data points distributed along the line when popularity equals, and the other group distributed between the band .pred = 25 and .pred = 50.

The following graph provides a closer look at the residuals.

One group of residuals are along the zero line and the other implies a negative correlation between the response variable and residual. The negative trend that occurs in the residual plot indicates that the model fails to predict a portion of the popularity accurately. Further exploration of predictors and model selection and parameter tuning is needed if we want to optimize the predictability of the model.

Conclusion

In order to predict the popularity of a song, this project shows that with predictors instrumentalness,loudness, speechiness, valence, danceability, accousticness and time_signature, the random forest model with mtry = 5, min_n = 2 and trees = 1000 is best at predicting the target variable.

In addition, the project also reveals that both instrumentalness and loudness are important predictors, while instrumentalness has more impact on the predictability of a model.

However, this model is not optimal. Results in the final analysis section show that improvement is needed for accurate prediction. Further exploration can focus on including the interaction of predictors in feature engineering or include track_genre as a predictor if the time is not a concern. Alternatively, instead of defining predicting popularity as a regression problem, I can transform the research question into a classification one. Response variable can consists of 5 categories each corresponds to range 0-20, 20-40, 40-60, 60-80 and 80-100. This transformation can potentially solve the issues with large amount of zero in popularity.
